text: Neck Airway Injuries Management COMMON EPA June 03, 2025 Bridget Olsen, MD • Ryan Meehan, MD • Damien Carter, MD Based on a previous module by Brian J. Eastridge, MD, and Vincent Chong, MD OVERVIEW CONFERENCE PREP RESOURCES Learning Objectives Anatomy The neck is divided into 3 zones from inferior to superior including 2 triangles. Zone I, sternal notch to the cricoid cartilage, includes subclavian vessels, internal jugular veins, proximal carotid arteries, vertebral arteries, apices of the lung, trachea, esophagus, spinal cord, thoracic duct, and thyroid gland. Zone II, cricoid cartilage to angle of the mandible, includes common carotid arteries and their branches, vertebral arteries, jugular veins, trachea, larynx, esophagus, pharynx, spinal cord, vagus nerves, and recurrent laryngeal nerves. Zone III, angle of the mandible to base of the skull, includes the distal internal carotid arteries, vertebral arteries, jugular veins, pharynx, spinal cord, and cranial nerves IX through XII. Anterior triangle of the neck is bounded by the sternocleidomastoid (SCM) muscle, lower border of the mandible, and the anterior cervical midline. Posterior triangle of the neck is bounded by the posterior aspect of the SCM muscle, the clavicle, and the trapezius muscle. The esophagus lies directly posterior to the trachea within the pretracheal fascia, which descends from the larynx into the mediastinum. Patterns of Injury Epidemiology Aerodigestive tract injuries are rare but potentially life threatening. Penetrating mechanisms are more likely than blunt mechanisms to cause either tracheobronchial or pharyngoesophageal injuries, with some studies reporting a 10- to 20-fold greater incidence. Patients with tracheobronchial injuries often die before they can be transported to a trauma center. The estimated incidence of traumatic tracheobronchial injury is 2% to 3%. Penetrating injury to the neck is associated with an approximate 5% incidence of esophageal injury. Outcomes Tracheobronchial injury can be associated with life-threatening airway loss, asphyxia, hemorrhage, aspiration, and tension pneumothorax. Penetrating laryngotracheal trauma mortality is 20%. Pharyngoesophageal injury can be associated with aspiration and delayed mediastinal or thoracic infection. Delayed recognition of pharyngoesophageal injuries and subsequent infection is the leading cause of delayed death from neck trauma. Mortality is as high as 22%; morbidity and mortality increases if diagnosed more than 24 hours after presentation. Evaluation and Initial Management Initial management First determine if the patient is unable to breathe or hard signs of aerodigestive tract injury or vascular injury are present. Hard signs of aerodigestive tract injury include air bubbling from a penetrating wound, active hemorrhage (ie massive hemoptysis or hematemesis, pulsatile or expanding hematoma), significant subcutaneous emphysema, and significant respiratory distress. If the patient is unstable or stable with hard signs, perform advanced trauma life support (ATLS), secure the airway, assess for other life-threatening injuries, and do rapid surgical exploration. In patients with blunt trauma and concern for tracheal injury, ensure successful ventilation with a bag valve mask before rapid sequence intubation (RSI). Paralysis can result in loss of airway and respiratory demise. A blowing air or “sucking” wound can indicate tracheal injury. Patients can rapidly decompensate during intubation and may require a

surgical airway (or, if able, secure the airway in the OR). Soft signs of aerodigestive tract injury include proximity of injury to the trachea and esophagus, mild subcutaneous emphysema, pneumomediastinum, mild hemoptysis or hematemesis, dysphagia, and dysphonia. CTA evaluates for potential neurovascular and aerodigestive tract injury. Thin-slice CT has high sensitivity for detecting laryngotracheal injuries. Temporizing measures include digital occlusion of hemorrhaging vessels or placement of a Foley catheter in the wound (clamped). Place intravascular lines on the contralateral side. Notes on further workup Patients with unexplained subcutaneous or mediastinal emphysema or other clinical signs of airway injury should be evaluated further with laryngoscopy and bronchoscopy. CT is less sensitive for identifying pharyngoesophageal injuries, with some reports noting sensitivity as low as 53%. However, CT imaging can show trajectories of penetrating injuries and associated pneumomediastinum, which require further imaging. For suspected esophageal injuries, esophagoscopy and contrast studies are complementary. The combination of esophagoscopy and esophagography (water-soluble contrast followed by thin barium) provides almost 100% sensitivity. Grading American Association of the Surgery of Trauma: Grade I: contusion, hematoma, or partial-thickness laceration Grade II: laceration ≤50% of circumference Grade III: laceration ≥50% of circumference Grade IV: segmental loss or devascularization ≤2 cm Grade V: segmental loss or devascularization ≥2 cm Schaefer classification for tracheal injuries: Grade 1: Minor endolaryngeal hematomas or lacerations without detectable fractures Grade 2: More severe edema, hematoma, minor mucosal disruption without exposed cartilage, or nondisplaced fractures Grade 3: Massive edema, large mucosal lacerations, exposed cartilage, displaced fractures or vocal cord immobility Grade 4: More severe massive edema, large mucosal lacerations, exposed cartilage, displaced fractures or vocal cord immobility with disruption of the anterior larynx, unstable fractures, ≥2 fracture lines, or severe mucosal injuries Grade 5: Complete laryngotracheal separation Operative Treatment (General Concepts) Positioning The patient should be supine with a shoulder roll; prep the neck and full chest in case of sternotomy or thoracotomy. Lateral decubitus is another option for stable patients with known distal esophageal injuries; however, in the setting of trauma, this position is not commonly used. Incision placement should be based on injury location for the best exposure. Basic tenets of surgical repair for aerodigestive tract injuries Due to the segmental vascular supply to both the trachea and esophagus, mobilization should be done only for adequate debridement and a tension-free repair or anastomosis. Basic principles for repair include: Debriding nonviable tissue Identifying the full extent of mucosal injury Undertaking primary repair for less than 50% circumferential injury for esophageal injuries (<1/3 for tracheal) Undertaking segmental resection and anastomosis for more than 50% circumferential injury Doing a tension-free repair Buttressing the repair with available muscle, pericardium, or pleura (helps strengthen the repair and decrease the risk for fistula) Ensuring contamination control For high-grade esophageal injuries or in patients with hemodynamic instability, performing proximal diversion with a cervical esophagostomy and distal esophageal ligation may be necessary. Most tracheal injuries

are related to penetrating injuries with minimal tissue loss. In these cases, a single layer interrupted 3-0 monofilament absorbable suture can be used for a primary repair. Protective tracheostomy: done for crush injuries to the trachea, tears more than 1/3 of the circumference, major laryngeal injuries, and when needed for other reasons (eg, expected prolonged ventilatory support).

Hand Injuries UNCOMMON March 14, 2025 Ravi F. Sood, MD • Ashleigh M. Francis, MD • Simon G. Talbot, MD OVERVIEW CONFERENCE PREP RESOURCES Learning Objectives Indications and Contraindications In a patient with hand trauma, be able to examine the extremity and determine if there is injury to the flexor digitorum superficialis (FDS), flexor digitorum profundus (FDP), and/or extensor tendon. FDS function is assessed by asking the patient to flex the finger at the proximal interphalangeal (PIP) joint while holding the other fingers in extension. FDP function is assessed by asking the patient to flex the finger at the distal interphalangeal (DIP) joint while holding the PIP joint in extension. Extensor tendon function is assessed by asking the patient to extend a finger against resistance with the terminal extensor and central slip acting to extend the DIP and PIP joints, respectively. Sabiston Textbook of Surgery, 21st ed. Figure 70-11. Individual clinical testing of the flexor digitorum profundus (A), flexor digitorum superficialis (B), flexor pollicis longus (C), finger extensors (D), and thumb extensors (E). In a patient with a tendon injury, be able to explain how timing may affect which operation is selected and required to achieve successful repair. Immediate (< 24 hours) or delayed primary (within 2 weeks) repair is ideal when possible. If there is a longer interval between injury and repair, tendon grafting or tendon transfer may be necessary. Rehabilitation protocols must balance the risk of rupture against the risk of adhesion formation and stiffness. Operative Anatomy In a patient with a tendon injury, be able to identify the basic neurovascular anatomy, tendon anatomy, and pulley anatomy required to avoid injury to these structures. The FDS tendon divides into two slips (Camper chiasm) and inserts on the volar aspect of the middle phalanx. The FDP tendon passes through the FDS tendon just proximal to the FDS insertion and inserts distally on the volar aspect of the distal phalanx. The neurovascular bundles run on the radial and ulnar aspects of each finger, with the nerve lying volar to the artery in the finger and dorsal to the artery in the palm. The flexor tendon sheath, which contains the flexor tendons in the finger, is made up of thicker, firmer annular pulleys A1 to A5 and thinner, more compressible cruciate pulleys C1 to C3. The A2 and A4 pulleys, which overlie the proximal and middle phalanges respectively, are most important to prevent bowstringing during finger flexion. In a patient with a known tendon injury, be able to name the zones of injury—especially as these pertain to treatment. Flexor tendon injuries are categorized into five anatomic zones. Zone I: distal to the FDS insertion on the middle phalanx Zone II: between the FDS insertion on the middle phalanx (distally) and the A1 pulley overlying the metacarpophalangeal (MP) joint (proximally) Zone III: between the A1 pulley over the MP joint (distally) and the distal extent of the carpal tunnel (proximally) Zone IV: within the carpal tunnel Zone V: proximal to the carpal tunnel Sabiston Textbook of Surgery, 21st ed. Figure 70-20. Zones of flexor tendon injuries on the fingers, thumb, and hand. Extensor tendon injuries are categorized into nine anatomic zones. Zone I: over the DIP joint Zone II: over the middle phalanx Zone III: over

the PIP joint Zone IV: over the proximal phalanx Zone V: over the MP joint Zone VI: over the metacarpal Zone VII: over the carpus Zone VIII: over the distal forearm and extensor retinaculum Zone IX: over the proximal forearm Preoperative Preparation In a patient with a tendon injury, be able to describe the concept and use of a tendon graft, two-stage repair, or tendon transfer required when direct repair is not optimal. Single-stage tendon graft reconstruction requires an adequate tendon sheath. The palmaris longus is a commonly used donor tendon. If the tendon sheath is absent or scarred, two-stage reconstruction, consisting of silicone rod placement and pseudosheath formation followed by tendon grafting, may be necessary. Tendon transfer may be required if the proximal muscle is nonfunctional. Key Steps of the Procedure In a patient with a flexor or extensor tendon injury, be able to demonstrate the variety of operative incisions required to gain access to perform the repair. Midlateral or Bruner (zigzag) incisions are typically used, incorporating existing skin lacerations when possible and optimizing access to both tendon ends. Avoiding incisions that cross flexion creases perpendicularly minimizes flexion contracture formation. In a patient with a flexor or extensor tendon injury, be able to describe the characteristics of suture techniques required for an effective tendon repair. Key common features include the following: At least four core suture strands across the repair Sabiston Textbook of Surgery, 21st ed. Figure 70-22. Technique of performing a four-strand flexor tendon core suture repair is demonstrated in association with a peripheral running suture. An epitendinous suture layer when the repair must pass through the pulley mechanism Intraoperative Decision Making In a patient with a tendon injury, be able to demonstrate the appropriate suture choice and technique required for successful repair. Tendon repairs are typically performed using braided permanent sutures. Key principles include the following: Minimizing tendon handling Placing sutures about 1 cm from the tendon ends Ensuring proper tendon orientation Minimizing the bulk of the repair Ensuring strength of repair with no gapping Confirming smooth gliding within the tendon sheath (when present) Complications and their Treatment In a patient who has undergone flexor tendon repair, be able to recognize repair rupture and formulate a plan for correction required to achieve satisfactory outcome. Repair rupture often presents as an acute “pop” with recurrence of presenting symptom (eg, loss of flexion or extension, depending on the tendon repaired). In the case of rupture, exploration and repeat repair are generally recommended. Long-term Follow-up Following tendon repair, be able to measure active, passive, and total range of motion required for following and documenting progress. Passive range of motion refers to motion that can be achieved through manipulating the joints with no effort from the patient. Active range of motion is that achieved with the patient's using his or her own muscles without assistance. Normal joint motions: Normal MP joint motion: 0 degrees of extension to 90 degrees of flexion Normal PIP joint motion: 5 degrees of hyperextension to 110 degrees of flexion Normal DIP joint motion: 30 degrees of hyperextension to 90 degrees of flexion In a patient who has undergone successful tendon repair, be able to recognize the indications and prerequisites for further surgery required to obtain optimal results. Stiffness is common following tendon repair. Extensive hand therapy resulting in maximal passive range of motion is critical prior to undertaking tenolysis to improve active range of motion.

Tracheobronchial and Lung Injury COMMON EPA March 12, 2025 Erika Borgerding Call, MD • Preston R. Miller III, MD OVERVIEW CONFERENCE PREP RESOURCES Learning Objectives Physiology In a patient with significant chest trauma, understand the cause of a pulmonary contusion. A pulmonary contusion is caused by transfer of energy through the chest wall. It may not show up on initial imaging, and it may develop over several days. However, a contusion that does show up on initial imaging is generally more severe, and the time to occurrence of respiratory failure is often shorter. In a patient with significant chest trauma, be able to describe the underlying pathophysiology that leads to the decline in respiratory status. Factors such as tissue damage, hemorrhage, and physiologic shunting lead to hypoxia. For significant contusions, the inflammatory response may be severe and lead to multisystem organ failure. Diagnosis (Physical Findings) In a patient who presents to the ED with chest trauma, be able to describe findings on physical examination that correlate with a tracheobronchial injury. These include: Extensive subcutaneous emphysema Continuous large air leaks after chest tube placement Hemoptysis In a patient with a stab wound to the chest, identify a massive hemothorax that needs operative intervention. Massive hemothorax includes output of 1500 mL or more on initial placement of a thoracostomy tube. It can also be indicated by ongoing bleeding of >300 mL/h for three consecutive hours. Although initial output is helpful in identifying patients that require thoracotomy, it should rarely be the sole indicator used. One must be wary of patients who have delayed placement of a chest tube, such as those who are transferred from an outside facility or those who spent a long time at the scene, because blood has had time to accumulate and initial output may be high. Thus, one should rely on signs of ongoing bleeding rather than initial output alone in making the decision to operate. Diagnosis (Testing and Interpretation) In a patient with chest trauma and a massive air leak after placement of a chest tube, be able to recognize the potential of a tracheobronchial injury and the need for emergent bronchoscopy in the operating room. A massive air leak after placement of a chest tube may indicate a tracheobronchial injury. Diagnosis of this injury can be made with bronchoscopy. If the injury is significant or causing respiratory distress, careful consideration must be taken to establish a definitive airway. An awake intubation over a flexible bronchoscope with placement of the endotracheal tube beyond the injury is ideal, but depending on the extent of the injury, other options may be indicated. Operative Treatment (General Concepts) Be able to discuss the operative management of tracheobronchial injuries. The operative approach depends on the location of the injury. Bronchoscopy should be performed first to locate the injury (see Learning Objective 3). For injuries to the trachea, right bronchus, and proximal left mainstem bronchus, a right thoracotomy incision is needed. For injures to the distal left airways, a left thoracotomy is needed. Devitalized tissue should be debrided and primary anastomosis using absorbable suture should be performed. An intercostal tissue flap to improve healing should be considered. In a patient with a gunshot wound to the chest and a bleeding pulmonary laceration in the periphery of the lung, be able to perform a stapled wedge resection of the laceration or an oversewing of the laceration with monofilament suture. In order to obtain hemostasis in a peripheral injury, it may be necessary to perform a stapled wedge resection. Inspection of the staple line should be made to locate any bleeding vessels, which should

be oversewn. In a patient with a gunshot wound to the chest and a bleeding pulmonary laceration in the central portion of the lobe, describe a tractotomy and oversewing of the bleeders with monofilament suture. For injuries closer to the central portion of the lung: A stapler is inserted through the injury and a tract is made that extends from the periphery to the injury. The staple line is inspected for any bleeding and is oversewn. In a patient with difficult-to-control bleeding laceration to the lung, describe both temporary hemorrhage control maneuvers and definitive techniques. During thoracotomy, if massive hemorrhage is encountered, some temporary damage control maneuvers can be used to stop the hemorrhage, which include hilar clamping and lung twisting. For hilar clamping, essentially a large clamp is secured over all the hilar structures to stop blood flow to that entire lung. To perform a hilar lung twist, the entire lung is twisted 180 degrees or more to stop blood flow. These damage control maneuvers can generally cause significant hemodynamic and respiratory compromise in the young healthy patient and should only be done for a short period of time. More definitive techniques for control of massive hemorrhage include lobectomy and nonanatomic resection (segment of lung), which are tolerated better than pneumonectomy (whole lung). Nonoperative Management, including Alternative and Adjuvant Treatments Describe the nonoperative management of patients with hemo- or pneumothorax and patients with tracheobronchial injuries. Nonoperative management of pneumothorax or hemothorax is most often done with placement of a chest tube. The goal is to remove the air or blood from the pleural space. In our practice, we manage chest tubes as follows: The chest tube is inserted on admission and placed to -20 mmHg suction for 24 hours. A CXR is obtained at the 24-hour mark, if the pneumothorax is resolved, the chest tube can be placed to water seal for 6 hours. Another CXR is obtained at the six-hour mark, and if there is no re-accumulation of the pneumothorax, the chest tube can be removed. For a hemothorax, if there are no signs of retained blood on the 24-hour CXR, we follow the same protocol as for pneumothorax. If there is an opacity suggesting retained hemothorax, we will obtain a non-contrasted CT chest. If the volume on the CT chest is significant, we will take the patient to the OR for video-assisted thoracoscopy (VATS). For tracheobronchial injuries that are less than one-third of the circumference of the bronchus, if the air leak is controlled by a chest tube, they may be treated nonoperatively. Patients must be admitted and closely observed, given humidified oxygen, and carefully suctioned.

Trauma in Pregnancy COMMON EPA March 12, 2025 Brian T. Young, MD • Vanessa P. Ho, MD • Catherine E. Lewis, MD OVERVIEW CONFERENCE PREP RESOURCES Learning Objectives Anatomy/Histology Understand maternal anatomic changes and fetal location and how they relate to the pregnant patient who suffers trauma. Early pregnancy The uterus remains shielded by the pelvis during the first 12 weeks of gestation. The pelvic bones and amniotic fluid cushion the developing fetus. Only 1% of blunt trauma results in direct fetal injury. The uterus reaches the level of the umbilicus by 20 weeks and then rises 1 cm per week on average. As the uterus rises, the bowel is displaced cephalad and lies mostly in the upper abdomen. As a result, the bowel is protected from blunt trauma by the ribs, and the uterus, placenta, and fetus are more vulnerable. Late pregnancy In the third trimester, the uterus thins, and the fetus is less protected. Unlike the myometrium of the uterus, which is more elastic, the placenta is relatively inelastic and subject to sheer force injury, such as abruptio placentae. Late in pregnancy, the fetus transitions to the vertex position with the head in the pelvis. Fetal skull fractures should be investigated in cases of deceleration injury. Maternal intra-abdominal organs are elevated during late pregnancy, with the diaphragm rising 4 cm. Penetrating injury to the lower thorax should raise suspicion for intra-abdominal injury. If chest tubes are indicated, caution should be used during placement due to the cephalad displacement of the diaphragm. Rebound tenderness and guarding secondary to intra-abdominal injury may be less prominent because the gravid uterus results in stretching of the anterior abdominal wall and impedes contact between areas of inflammation and the parietal peritoneum. At term, maternal uterine blood flow increases to 500 mL/min, or 17% of the cardiac output (compared to 50 mL/min at 10 weeks). Uterine veins may dilate to 60 times their prepregnant state. This increased vascularity carries an attendant risk of massive blood loss with pelvic injury. Pelvic fractures are the most common injury to the mother, resulting in fetal mortality approaching 35%. Physiology Understand the normal physiologic changes of pregnancy and how they relate to the evaluation of a pregnant patient who suffers traumatic injury. Maternal Circulatory Physiologic anemia of pregnancy: Plasma volume increases 45% with increased red blood cell volume of only 15%. This may mask hypotension secondary to blood loss. Supine hypotensive syndrome: When the mother is in the supine position, the fetus partially obstructs the inferior vena cava, reducing venous return to the heart by up to 30% when compared with left lateral positioning. This is marked by dizziness, pallor, tachycardia, sweating, nausea, and hypotension. Hematology: Leukocytosis, thrombocytopenia, and increased fibrinogen and clotting factors VII, VII, IX, and X, with decline of XI and XIII, may occur. Respiratory Increased subcostal angle, increased chest circumference, and increased diaphragmatic excursion overcome the elevated diaphragm, leading to increased tidal volume with reduced functional residual capacity (FRC) and a chronic compensated respiratory alkalosis. The compensatory decrease in plasma bicarbonate diminishes buffering ability. Oxygen consumption increases by almost 20%. This along with reduced FRC make apnea poorly tolerated, and supplemental oxygen is therefore always indicated. Gastrointestinal Decreased motility and esophageal sphincter competency place the mother at high risk for aspiration. Fetal The placental vasculature is maximally dilated throughout pregnancy but is exquisitely sensitive

to catecholamine stimulation. An abrupt decrease in maternal intravascular volume can result in a profound increase in uterine vascular resistance, reducing fetal oxygenation despite normal maternal vital signs. Mixing of amniotic fluid and maternal blood can result in amniotic fluid embolism and disseminated intravascular coagulation. It is important to understand that the best treatment for the fetus is treatment of the mother. Epidemiology Recognize the prevalence of trauma in pregnant women. Trauma affects 6% to 8% of pregnancies. A recent review reports the following prevalence by subtype of trauma: Domestic violence: 8307 of 100,000 live births Motor vehicle crash: 207 of 100,000 live births Falls: 49 of 100,000 live births Homicide: 3 of 100,000 live births Penetrating trauma: 3 of 100,000 live births Suicide: 2 of 100,000 live births Toxic exposure: 26 of 100,000 person-years Burns: 0.17 of 100,000 person-years Assessment Understand the proper assessment of a pregnant trauma patient, including the use of adjuncts unique to this population. The initial assessment is the same as for any trauma patient: Airway, Breathing, Circulation, and Disability. Keep in mind the anatomic and physiologic changes of pregnancy. It is important to note that the best initial treatment for the fetus is optimal treatment and resuscitation of the mother. The obstetrical service should be present during the assessment to help with the initial evaluation. A visual vaginal examination using a speculum should be performed to evaluate for bleeding or leakage of amniotic fluid. Measurement of fetal heart rate (FHR) is the minimum initial fetal assessment that should be performed. The normal FHR is 110 to 160 beats/min. If unknown, fetal age can be estimated using ultrasonography to measure biparietal diameter (BPD). A BPD of more than 58 mm corresponds to a viable pregnancy of more than 24 weeks. Recognize red flags that may signify physical abuse in a pregnant patient. It has been estimated that 6% to 22% of gravid women experience intimate partner violence during pregnancy. Intimate partner violence is the most common cause of trauma-related maternal death in pregnancy. Abused patients may initially delay medical attention or give implausible explanations for injuries. Examination findings concerning for abuse include cuts, bruises, or burns that do not match the reported mechanism; bruises or injuries in various stages of healing; restraint or grip markings; and repeated injuries. Proper referrals to social work and appropriate agencies should be performed in all cases of suspected abuse. Diagnosis In a pregnant trauma patient, be able to determine which diagnostic studies are required, including their relative indications and associated risks. The FAST examination should be performed to find pericardial or peritoneal fluid. It has 80% sensitivity and 100% specificity. The small amount of normal physiologic fluid (7-21 mL) is too small to be detected during a routine FAST examination, and a positive finding should always be considered pathologic. Always keep in mind that a negative FAST examination does not rule out intra-abdominal or fetal injury. CT scans should be obtained using the same indications as in nonpregnant patients and should not be withheld. CT is the mainstay for imaging in trauma, and the risk of missed injury is greater than the potential risk of radiation to the fetus. The best care for the fetus is always the best care for the mother. No study to date has shown any increase in teratogenicity above baseline at fetal exposures below 10 rad or 100 mGy to the fetus. The American College of Obstetrics and Gynecology (ACOG) has published guidelines stating that 5 rad or 50 mGy exposure to the fetus is not associated with any increased risk of fetal

loss or birth defects. The fetus should be shielded whenever possible. An ultrasound evaluation of the fetus and placenta is useful to determine gestational age and placental position and to evaluate and document fetal status. Fetal Focused Assessment with Sonography for Trauma (fetal FAST) consists of the following assessments: Number of fetuses and their position Placental location Amniotic fluid volume Fetal cardiac activity Femur length A formal obstetric ultrasound evaluation should be performed for any patient with abnormal findings on fetal FAST. The Kleihauer-Betke test should be routinely performed in all patients who are Rh-negative and should also be considered in Rh-positive patients who sustain blunt injury. A positive test is associated with abruptio placentae and is also a predictor of preterm labor. If the test is positive, and the mother is Rh-negative, the appropriate dose of Rh immune globulin should be given to prevent alloimmunization. Operative Treatment (General Concepts) Understand how pregnancy affects the operative management of traumatic injuries. To facilitate exploratory laparotomy for trauma, a generous vertical midline incision is made. Consideration to patient positioning should be made (eg, elevating the right side to avoid vena cava compression). Indications for emergency cesarean section are similar to that of nontrauma patients. If cesarean section is considered in cases of trauma, it should be ensured that saving the fetus will not adversely affect the maternal outcome. Emergency cesarean section should only be considered if the fetus is greater than 24 weeks' gestation. Special considerations and indications in trauma patients include facilitating surgical exposure for management of maternal injuries during laparotomy and potentially saving the mother if cardiopulmonary resuscitation has not been effective within 4 minutes. Perimortem cesarean section refers to that which is performed at the time of maternal death. An otherwise uninjured fetus delivered within 5 minutes of maternal death has a survival rate of up to 70%. Nonoperative Management, including Alternative and Adjuvant Treatments Understand the nonoperative management of pregnant trauma patients. Continuous fetal monitoring with fetal heart rate and uterine contraction monitoring should be performed in all trauma patients who are at more than 24 weeks' gestation. The recommended duration of monitoring is 2 to 6 hours, with most practitioners recommending a minimum of 4 hours. Patients with any of the following risks should be monitored for a minimum of 24 hours: Abdominal bruising or other obvious abdominal injury Persistent abdominal or uterine pain Maternal heart rate greater than 110 beats/min Regular contractions Vaginal bleeding Coagulopathy (eg, low platelets or fibrinogen) High-risk mechanism such as vehicle ejection, motorcycle crash, or death of another occupant in a motor vehicle collision Injury Severity Score (ISS) greater than 9 Evidence of placental abruption on ultrasound Describe the obstetrical complications that can occur in the pregnant trauma patient. The reported incidence of abruptio placentae after trauma ranges from 7.4% in patients with minor injury to 40% to 60% in patients who sustain severe trauma to the abdomen. Symptoms may include abdominal pain, contractions, uterine rigidity/tenderness, and vaginal bleeding. It is important to note that placental abruption can be present in the absence of vaginal bleeding. The fetal heart rate tracing can be either nonreassuring or normal. There is no single diagnostic test for abruptio placenta. Diagnosis is based on the constellation of symptoms, laboratory findings (such as low platelet count and fibrinogen concentration), and imaging, though no imaging modality is sufficiently sensitive. Uterine rupture can occur with severe blunt trauma or with penetrating injury. Signs and symptoms include shock, abnormal fetal heart rate tracing, uterine tenderness, vaginal bleeding, and palpation of fetal parts outside the

uterus. Other intra-abdominal injuries such as liver or splenic injury can present similarly and complicate the diagnosis. Diagnosis is generally made either by imaging or by emergency exploratory laparotomy. Fetomaternal bleeding has been reported in up to 30% of pregnant trauma patients. Patients are often asymptomatic, though abdominal or uterine tenderness should raise suspicion. The diagnosis is made by the Kleihauer-Betke test, which measures the percent of red cells containing fetal hemoglobin in maternal blood. Complications of fetomaternal bleeding include fetal anemia, maternal alloimmunization, and fetal death. Amniotic fluid embolism is a rare but typically catastrophic complication. The incidence is not known and is limited to case reports. Signs and symptoms include severe respiratory difficulty and hypoxia, seizures, disseminated intravascular coagulopathy, or sudden cardiovascular collapse.

Pelvic Fractures and Retroperitoneal Hematoma COMMON EPA March 12, 2025 Kirellos Zamary, MD • David Spain, MD OVERVIEW CONFERENCE PREP RESOURCES Learning Objectives Anatomy/Histology Identify the zones of the retroperitoneum and describe the approximate borders and contents of each zone. Zone I (central): contains the major vessels (aorta and inferior vena cava) Zone II (lateral): contains the renal vessels and kidneys Zone III (pelvis): contains the iliac arteries and veins In a plain radiograph of the pelvis, identify the major bony structures of the pelvis (pubic rami, symphysis, ilia, and sacrum) and recognize the distinguishing features of stable and unstable pelvic fractures. Stable injuries are nondisplaced fractures or those with less than 2.5 cm of displacement of the pubic symphysis. Unstable fractures can be detected by deformity or displacement of the pubic symphysis by greater than 2.5 cm. Pelvic instability should not be missed because it requires urgent stabilization and control of potentially fatal hemorrhage. Images courtesy of Kirellos Zamary, MD. Epidemiology Describe the mechanisms by which pelvic fractures and retroperitoneal hemorrhage occur. The top three mechanisms for pelvic fractures include motor vehicle or motorcycle crashes, pedestrians struck by motor vehicles, and falls. Retroperitoneal hematoma may be associated with blunt or penetrating trauma, with a preponderance for blunt trauma. Physiology Understand and describe the “lethal triad” associated with massive hemorrhage that can accompany retroperitoneal and/or pelvic hemorrhage. The lethal triad is coagulopathy, acidosis, and hypothermia. Damage-control laparotomy may be necessary, depending on the physiologic changes that follow massive hemorrhage. Understand the physiologic effects of prolonged ischemia-reperfusion after cross-clamping of the aorta following resuscitative thoracotomy, resuscitative endovascular balloon occlusion of the aorta (REBOA), or prolonged vessel clamping for vascular injury repair. After unclamping of a cross-clamped aorta or after REBOA deflation, there is a sudden decrease in aortic afterload, a rapid influx of blood into dilated distal vasculature and then a washout of ischemic metabolites. Tissue ischemia results in the formation of reactive oxygen species and changes in mitochondrial permeability. Tissue hypoxia also leads to a proinflammatory cascade and nitric oxide release. Restoration of blood flow paradoxically often results in further tissue injury. This requires timely communication and coordination with the anesthesiologist. Diagnosis (Physical Findings) As part of the initial ATLS survey in blunt trauma, be able to examine a patient for evidence of a pelvic fracture and associated genitourinary injury, and if urethral injury is suspected, perform retrograde urethrography prior to Foley catheter insertion. Flank or buttock contusions and swelling suggest significant bleeding, as do proximal thigh ecchymosis (Fox sign) or scrotal ecchymosis (Bryant sign). Gentle palpation of the pubic symphysis and sacroiliac joints evaluates for pain in the awake patient, and lateral compression through the anterior iliac crests helps determine pelvic stability. Signs of associated genitourinary injury include blood at the urethral meatus; a high-riding prostate; and blood, lacerations, or bony fragments found on rectal or vaginal examination. Know how to diagnose retroperitoneal hemorrhage and zone of hemorrhage on examination and intraoperatively. On examination, one may see flank ecchymosis (Grey Turner sign), umbilical ecchymosis (Cullen sign), proximal thigh ecchymosis (Fox

sign), or scrotal ecchymosis (Bryant sign). In the operating room, a hematoma or expanding hematoma may be seen in zones I to III during exploratory laparotomy. Evidence of a zone I injury would be seen either with kocherization or during exploration of the lesser sac. Diagnosis (Testing and Interpretation) Determine the appropriate indications for FAST, plain radiography of the pelvis, and multidetector CT in evaluating trauma patients with suspected pelvic injury. In addition, be able to interpret the results of each of these tests. ATLS recommends obtaining a portable anteroposterior (AP) radiograph of the pelvis in all blunt trauma patients with potential pelvic injury. The film identifies significant pelvic fractures, specifically displaced fractures and open-book injuries that would benefit from pelvic binding in the trauma bay. AP radiographs have the most utility in the patient who is too hemodynamically unstable for CT. A positive FAST in the hemodynamically unstable patient with a suspected pelvic fracture should prompt laparotomy for evaluation of concurrent abdominal hemorrhage. Multidetector CT is the gold standard for evaluating pelvic trauma in hemodynamically stable patients. It delineates fractures, localizes areas of arterial bleeding, determines the extent of retroperitoneal bleeding, and identifies associated injuries. Interpret the presence and zone of retroperitoneal hemorrhage on CT scan and know that FAST is not a sensitive tool to rule out retroperitoneal hemorrhage. Knowledge of the borders of zones I to III is paramount in determining the course of management based on the CT scan results. On CT, a hematoma or blush may be seen in zones I to III. Image courtesy of Kirellos Zamary, MD. Operative Treatment (General Concepts) Describe the major damage-control principles in operative management of severe pelvic fractures. External fixation starts in the trauma bay with wrapping the pelvis and can include placement of external fixators or pelvic C clamps in the operating room. For patients who remain hemodynamically unstable despite pelvic binding, resuscitative endovascular balloon placement is a nonoperative technique to temporize abdominal or pelvic/retroperitoneal bleeding until surgical or angiographic control of the bleeding is achieved. Control of hemorrhage may involve angioembolization or preperitoneal packing. Control of contamination consists of debridement of nonviable tissue and at minimum temporizing repair of associated genitourinary or rectal injuries, which may include diverting ostomy formation. Identify the zones of the retroperitoneum and know which retroperitoneal injuries require operative versus nonoperative management. Operative All zone I injuries All penetrating retroperitoneal injuries All expanding retroperitoneal hematomas Nonoperative Blunt zone II/III hematomas that are not expanding Describe the steps required to surgically access and explore the three retroperitoneal zones and address injuries therein. The suprarenal inframesocolic aorta is accessed via a left medial visceral rotation. The infrarenal aorta is accessed by reflecting the mesocolon cephalad with evisceration of the small bowel to the right and incising through the retroperitoneum overlying the aorta. Infrahepatic, suprarenal control of the IVC requires a Kocher maneuver. Control of bleeding at the iliac vein bifurcation may require division of the right common iliac artery. Describe the management of an expanding zone II hematoma. Expanding hematomas should be explored. Repair of renal artery transection is contraindicated in an unstable patient with a normal contralateral kidney; nephrectomy is the treatment of choice. Renal vein ligation without nephrectomy can be performed on the left (due to collateral venous flow), but a nephrectomy must follow a renal vein ligation on the right (potentially at a second operation in

the setting of damage control). Assessment of Outcomes In a trauma patient with a pelvic fracture, recognize the increased risk of developing DVT and pulmonary embolism and understand the importance of early DVT prophylaxis. There is a significantly increased incidence of thromboembolic complications in major trauma patients. Patients with major pelvic fractures, requiring operating fixation and prolonged immobilization, are at especially high risk. Low-molecular-weight heparin and sequential calf compression devices should be ordered as prophylaxis. If there is absolute contraindication to anticoagulation, consider retrievable IVC filters with caution because of the high rate of complications. In a trauma patient who has had a massive resuscitation and laparotomy for retroperitoneal hemorrhage, understand the risk of complications that may follow. Complications following massive resuscitation and control of retroperitoneal vascular injury include: Abdominal compartment syndrome Pancreatic fistula Major vessel venous or arterial thrombosis

file: Chest Wall, Pleura, and Diaphragm Injuries.txt
text: Chest Wall, Pleura, and Diaphragm Injuries COMMON EPA April 16, 2025 Ian Kratzke, MD • Jared Robert Gallaher, MD, MPH Based on a previous module by Rafael Torres-Fajardo, MD; Edgardo Salcedo, MD; and Gregory Jurkovich, MD OVERVIEW CONFERENCE PREP RESOURCES Learning Objectives Anatomy Thorax The neurovascular bundle runs inferior to the rib. It is essential to be aware of this relationship when performing a thoracotomy, tube thoracostomy, rib fixation, or nerve block to avoid damage to these structures. Rapid identification of the angle of Louis (sternomanubrial joint) serves as a landmark to identify the second intercostal space for needle decompression of tension pneumothorax. Diaphragm The diaphragm has 3 major foramina, allowing the passage of the inferior vena cava at level T8, the esophagus at T10, and the aorta at T12. The phrenic vein is located 1 cm above the esophageal hiatus. Injury to this vein can result in significant bleeding. The phrenic nerve arises at C3, C4, and C5. It runs through the posterolateral mediastinum to the caudal surface of the diaphragm. It gives rise to 4 branches spreading centrifugally, 1 anteriorly, 1 posteriorly, and 2 laterally. The location of the diaphragm is highly variable relative to the chest wall, so it is important to avoid placing chest tubes too low. Typically, a chest tube is placed at the anterior axillary line between the fourth and fifth intercostal space to avoid intra-abdominal placement. Physiology Pleura During penetrating chest trauma, air enters the thoracic cavity, either from a hole in the lung or from the outside. The potential space between the visceral and parietal peritoneum becomes real, and the lung collapses due to its elastic recoil, causing a pneumothorax. During blunt trauma, rib fractures can lacerate the lung. In addition, a sudden increase in intrathoracic pressure (direct blow, violent coughing) can result in alveolar rupture, leading to an air leak and pneumothorax. Injury to the chest may also result in pulmonary contusion because of the physical transfer of energy, leading to edema and hemorrhage of the lung. Physiologically, this causes hypoxemia from an increased shunt (blood flow to a nonaerated lung) and can also lead to carbon dioxide retention and respiratory acidosis due to the altered work of breathing. Diaphragm Blunt diaphragmatic injuries result from crush or blunt abdominal trauma when intra-abdominal pressure is increased. This increased pressure causes an increase in the pleuroperitoneal gradient, tearing the muscle. Given the high energy required to rupture the diaphragm, other associated injuries, such as hemothorax, pneumothorax, rib fractures, and splenic injuries, are common. Penetrating trauma, in contrast, causes short tears. Sternum Patients with sternal fractures caused by high-impact chest trauma can present with other associated injuries, including rib fractures, pulmonary contusions, and cardiac contusions. These patients are also at increased risk for extrathoracic injuries, including spinal fractures and cranial injuries. Diagnosis: Physical Findings Pneumothorax Patients with a pneumothorax can present either with or without symptoms. Physical findings include: Hypoxia Subcutaneous emphysema Decreased breath sounds Tension pneumothorax presents with: Hypotension Jugular venous distention (JVD) Tracheal deviation to the opposite side of the pneumothorax Cardiac tamponade Patients with cardiac tamponade may present with hypotension,

file: Chest Wall, Pleura, and Diaphragm Injuries.txt
text: JVD, and muffled heart sounds (Beck's triad). Fractures Patients with rib fractures may have pain, chest wall hemorrhage, crepitus, and chest wall instability. Flail chest is the term for multiple consecutive segmentally fractured ribs (at least three or more) causing delayed or asymmetrical rise in the affected chest wall. Some patients may present with actual paradoxical chest wall movement, but this is not required to make the diagnosis. Diaphragmatic injury In penetrating chest trauma, injury should be suspected in any trauma below the nipple. In addition, a diaphragm injury could be present in patients with hemothorax or pneumothorax and known liver or spleen injury. In blunt trauma, diaphragmatic injury should be suspected in high-velocity and quick deceleration events and blunt abdominal trauma. This injury is difficult to diagnose with a physical examination. Diagnosis: Imaging Hemothorax In chest trauma, it is important to understand how to identify a complete opacification or “white lung” and the need to place a chest tube. The presence of blood or fluid may cause compression and deviation of the mediastinal structures to the contralateral side. This contrasts with lung collapse, in which structures deviate toward the affected lung. In the supine position, chest x-ray (CXR) reveals hemothorax when 200 to 300 mL of blood is present. Pneumothorax On CXR, patients with pneumothorax will not have lung markings extending to the edge of the ribs. A tension pneumothorax is a clinical rather than radiological diagnosis as it indicates that a patient is hypotensive from loss of venous return to the heart due to compression from the pneumothorax. There may also be a component of hemothorax in patients with concomitant pneumothorax. Sensitivity for pneumothorax on CXR is increased when the patient is placed in an upright position. CXR interpretation includes evaluation of: Degree of penetration Abnormalities of lung parenchyma and pleura (lung expansion, contusion, pneumothoraces, and hemothoraces) Abnormalities of the trachea and bronchi Position of endotracheal tube and lines Presence of rib or bone fractures Ultrasound is another useful adjunct and is more sensitive than CXR in visualizing small hemothoraces and pneumothoraces. CT remains the gold standard for detecting small pneumothoraces. When a pneumothorax is demonstrated on CT but not CXR, it is considered an “occult” pneumothorax. Aortic injury In the National Trauma Data Bank, aortic injury was present in only 0.3% of patients sustaining blunt trauma, although the associated mortality exceeds 37%. CXR The most sensitive indicator of blunt aortic injury is an abnormal or widened mediastinum (> 6 cm on an upright posteroanterior CXR; > 8 cm or > 25% of transthoracic diameter at the level of the aortic arch on a supine anteroposterior CXR). Other findings of mediastinal hematoma include left apical cap, right tracheal shift or right enteric tube shift, inferior displacement of left mainstem bronchus, and blunting of aortic knob. Most signs are present in 30% to 70% of patients. Only 12.5% of mediastinal hematomas result from aortic injury. However, the negative predictive value of a normal CXR of high quality is approximately 97%, but this may reflect the low incidence of blunt thoracic aortic injury. First rib fracture indicates severe trauma and the possibility of traumatic aortic injury (15%–30% frequency). Cardiac echocardiography to evaluate for tamponade is a part of the FAST exam.

file: Chest Wall, Pleura, and Diaphragm Injuries.txt
text: Contrast CT is the most sensitive exam for aortic injury and helps grade the severity of the injury. Fractures CXR Rib fractures may be difficult to identify on plain film unless significantly displaced. Clavicular fractures are more easily identified on CXR. CT CT helps differentiate between pleural fluid collections and parenchymal injury in stable patients, as seen in pulmonary contusions. CT is more sensitive than CXR in the detection of rib and sternal fractures. CT of the thoracic spine is the gold standard for assessing vertebral body and posterior element fractures. Diaphragmatic injury CXR Flattening of the diaphragm or the presence of a nasogastric tube or gastric bubble in the left hemithorax is indicative of diaphragmatic injury. CT CT is more sensitive than CXR in identifying a diaphragmatic injury, but one may still not be evident, especially if it is right-sided as the liver may obscure the defect. If a diaphragmatic injury is suspected (eg, thoracoabdominal injuries), despite negative imaging findings, laparotomy, diagnostic laparoscopy, or video-assisted thoracoscopic surgery (VATS) should be performed. Operative Management Hemothorax/pneumothorax The treatment goal for hemothorax and pneumothorax is evacuation of the pleural space and re-expansion of the lung. This is done by tube thoracostomy, followed by CXR to verify the position of the chest tube. After completion of tube thoracostomy for hemothorax, the chest tube must be monitored. Emergent thoracotomy is suggested when the initial output is 1 L of blood or there is continued chest output of 200 mL/h for 4 hours. If hemothoraces remain after chest tube drainage or if there are persistent air leaks with pneumothoraces, VATS may be required to wash out retained hemothorax or intervene on a persistent bronchial injury with the possibility of a lung resection. Fractures Indications for operative fixation of rib fractures: Severely displaced fractures in patients undergoing thoracotomies for associated intrathoracic injuries Progressive deterioration of pulmonary function despite aggressive nonoperative pain management Pulmonary contusions and associated rib fractures in patients who are unable to be weaned from the ventilator after contusions have resolved Significant chest wall deformity and nonunion of fractures Indications for operative fixation of sternal fractures include: Unstable fractures Fractures associated with infection Fractures can be repaired with plates, intramedullary devices, vertical bridging prostheses, and sternal wires. Chronic pain Diaphragmatic injury Acute diaphragmatic injuries are best repaired through the abdomen. This approach allows the evaluation of other associated intra-abdominal injuries. The best approach for chronic diaphragmatic injuries is through the thorax. Operative steps include debridement of obviously necrotic tissue, eversion of borders for adequate approximation (when primary repair is feasible) either with stay sutures or an Allis clamp, the use of nonabsorbable sutures, and interrupted or running suture primary repair (surgeon preference). Injury to the phrenic nerve should be avoided. When a central defect does not allow primary tension-free repair, there are 2 options: The peripheral attachments can be incised anteriorly, laterally, and posteriorly from their costal origins to close the defect, and the diaphragm is reattached 2 to 3 interspaces more cephalad. The defect can be repaired with biological or synthetic mesh material. Nonoperative Management Patients with chest trauma require early pain control with multimodal pain regimens, as they often have poor inspiratory effort and splinting, leading to hypoventilation, atelectasis, pneumonia (due to retained secretions), and respiratory failure. Respiratory support with mechanical ventilation

file: Chest Wall, Pleura, and Diaphragm Injuries.txt
text: for several days is sometimes required to manage significant pulmonary contusion and flail chest. Aggressive pulmonary toilet, incentive spirometry, adequate analgesia, and multimodal pain management are critical in the nonoperative management of these patients. Pain management consists of: IV medications (opioids, ketorolac), which are essential for early pain control Oral medications (eg, NSAIDs, acetaminophen, opioids, gabapentin, muscle relaxants), which are critical for long-term pain control Epidural analgesia Elastomeric pumps, which automatically and continuously deliver a regulated flow of local anesthetic via a subcutaneous-paravertebral catheter Understanding the venous plasma concentration of local anesthetic agents and their clinical implications is vital.

Splenic Injury COMMON EPA March 12, 2025 Darren Bowe, MD • Joseph Cuschieri, MD OVERVIEW CONFERENCE PREP RESOURCES Learning Objectives Anatomy/Histology Identify the ligamentous attachments to the spleen. Splenophrenic ligament: avascular when no portal hypertension is present Splenorenal ligament: avascular when no portal hypertension is present Gastrosplenic ligament: short gastric arteries superiorly Splenocolic ligament: avascular Understand important anatomic relationships of the spleen that could be used to identify injury to the spleen or associated structures. Located in left upper quadrant and superiorly attached to diaphragm via splenophrenic ligament and left ribs 9-12. Injury to the left lower ribs could be an indication of associated splenic injury. Posteriorly associated with left adrenal gland and left kidney. Medially intimately associated with tail of pancreas, identification of this association is essential in safe mobilization of the spleen. Inferiorly closely associated with splenic flexure of the colon and transverse colon. Important during splenectomy to carefully inspect these associated structures for signs of injury. Presentation In a patient with suspected splenic injury, rapidly assess the patient's hemodynamic status in order to determine subsequent steps in management (ie, operative intervention vs imaging). All trauma care should begin with the Advanced Trauma Life Support (ATLS) algorithm. The primary survey includes securing the airway, ensuring appropriate breathing, rapidly assessing circulation (ie, bleeding), determining the Glasgow Coma Scale score, and obtaining exposure of the patient. Mechanism of injury, tachycardia, hypotension, and positive intra-abdominal blood on Focused Assessment for the Sonographic evaluation of the Trauma patient (FAST) should prompt providers to assess for hemorrhage from possible splenic compromise (among other sources). If the patient’s symptoms do not respond to resuscitation, he or she should be brought to the operating room for immediate trauma laparotomy prior to secondary survey and imaging. However, if the patient responds to resuscitation, secondary survey should be completed and imaging considered. In a patient with blunt abdominal trauma, recognize the signs, symptoms, and injury patterns that may be associated with splenic injury. Hypovolemic shock: hypotension and tachycardia that may or may not respond to resuscitation "Seat belt" sign or flank bruising Referred abdominal pain to the left shoulder (Kehr sign) Associated injuries that carry a high risk of concomitant splenic injury (left rib cage, pelvic fracture, or spinal damage) Diagnosis In a hemodynamically normal patient with blunt abdominal trauma, complete the primary and secondary survey and then obtain a computed tomography (CT) scan of the abdomen when appropriate. If presentation suggests intra-abdominal pathology, imaging of the abdomen is appropriate. CT of the abdomen with intravenous contrast is the most valuable study for characterizing splenic injuries. It is necessary to look for active extravasation of intravenous contrast or the presence of a pseudoaneurysm. Active extravasation In a patient with blunt abdominal trauma and shock, use FAST to check for hemoperitoneum. FAST examination can aid in the diagnosis of intra-abdominal bleeding. Identification of intra-abdominal fluid with ongoing shock should prompt emergent laparotomy. In a hemodynamically stable patient with a splenic injury identified on CT scan, evaluate for associated injuries, such as pancreatic or renal injury, before selecting operative or nonoperative management. Associated injuries are common and can help dictate care. Overall, up to 3% of patients have been reported to have a hollow viscus injury. If additional injuries requiring operative intervention are discovered, splenectomy versus splenic salvage procedures should be considered. Staging/Grading Describe how to grade a splenic injury using the American Association

for the Surgery of Trauma (AAST) Injury Scale. Grade I Grade II Grade III Grade IV Grade V Operative Treatment (General Concepts) Verbalize the key surgical steps of an open splenectomy in a trauma patient. The many approaches to splenectomy are determined by clinician preference, need for splenectomy, and patient stability. After splenic trauma, key steps include: Perform a midline laparotomy. Pack all four quadrants. Remove the packing in order of areas least likely to have bleeding. Divide lateral attachments by moving the spleen medially. Divide the splenocolic ligament starting at the white line of Toldt. Divide the short gastric arteries and gastrosplenic ligament. Bluntly dissect posterior to the spleen and distal pancreas to deliver the spleen into the field. (Make the spleen a midline structure) Clamp and divide the splenic artery and vein. In a patient with splenic injury requiring removal or repair, it is necessary to: Divide the splenic ligaments safely and achieve homeostasis. Bluntly dissect the retroperitoneal attachments and achieve delivery of the spleen into the wound. This allows for quick identification and clamping of the splenic hilar vessels. Be aware of and recognize early and late complications following open splenectomy. Early Bleeding: usually from raw surfaces of divided ligaments or short gastric arteries that have been in spasm. Look for hypotension, tachycardia, and downtrending hematocrit/hemoglobin. Gastric perforation: rare from division of the short gastric arteries too close to the stomach. Late Overwhelming postsplenectomy infection (OPSI): most common fatal late complication. This is heralded by an early prodromal phase of fevers, rigors, chills, diarrhea, and myalgia. It rapidly progresses to multisystem organ failure, disseminated intravascular coagulation, and death (50%-70%). Thrombocytosis: more prevalent with underlying myeloproliferative disorders. Bleeding. Delayed bleeding occurs in less than 1% of cases. The risk is greater in patients who have more severe injuries. Pancreatic fistula/leak: pain, leukocytosis, systemic inflammatory response. Occurs secondary to intimate association with tail of pancreas and splenic hilum. Be able to determine the need for, and timing of, postsplenectomy vaccinations. Vaccination for encapsulated organisms: Neisseria meningitides (polysaccharide vaccine), Streptococcus pneumoniae (23-valent polysaccharide vaccine not the 14-valent one), and Haemophilus influenzae (type B conjugate) Elective splenectomy: 15 days prior Nonelective splenectomy: within 30 days (best if occurs prior to discharge from the hospital). Nonoperative Management, including Alternative and Adjuvant Treatments In a patient with a splenic injury whose CT scan of the abdomen demonstrates an arterial extravasation or a pseudoaneurysm, recommend angiographic embolization. (Results are similar with central and peripheral splenic artery embolization.) Both diagnostic and therapeutic intervention are important. Patients in shock should not be considered for angiography. In a hemodynamically stable patient with a splenic injury visible on CT scan, admit the patient for nonoperative management. Monitor the patient’s vital signs; perform serial physical examinations; and order intermittent laboratory studies, including hemoglobin and/or hematocrit as appropriate. Most patients are no longer bleeding at presentation and thus do not require splenectomy. Any sign of ongoing bleeding and/or shock usually indicates failure of nonoperative management. In a patient with a splenic injury who is undergoing nonoperative management, recognize the presence of ongoing hemorrhage and determine an appropriate treatment plan for either operative exploration or

angiographic embolization. Patients with greater bleeding risk (pseudoaneurysm, "blush") often can be managed with angioembolization. Any sign of shock should prompt emergent operation and possible repair or splenectomy. Be able to identify patients at higher risk for failure of nonoperative management. Nonoperative treatment has a failure rate of 6% to 15% depending on the degree of injury. Patients with abnormal coagulation status or preexisting splenic disease are more likely to fail nonoperative management. Although nonoperative treatment is more likely to fail in patients older than 55 years, it is still successful in more than 80% of these cases. Patients with grade IV and V injuries have up to a 33% and 75% risk of failure of nonoperative treatment failure, respectively, with 92% of these failures occurring by 9 days post-injury. Long-term Follow-up In a patient who has had successful nonoperative management of a splenic injury, recommend an appropriate period of time, based on the grade of the injury, before allowing the patient to return to full activity. The patient should wait 3 months before engaging in vigorous activity. However, data for sound guidance are lacking. Eighty percent of patients have splenic healing by 2 months (excluding grades IV-V). In a patient with imaging findings of a splenic pseudoaneurysm, arteriovenous fistula, or high-grade injury, be able to discuss the role of repeat CT imaging and angioembolization. The Eastern Association for the Surgery of Trauma (EAST) splenic trauma guidelines (2012) do not recommend routine follow-up imaging after nonoperative management. Up to 15% of patients will develop a pseudoaneurysm, half of which spontaneously thrombose.

file: Management of Vascular Injuries to the Neck.txt
text: Management of Vascular Injuries to the Neck COMMON EPA March 12, 2025 Tony Boualoy, MD • Alexandra Helbing, MD • Eric Schupp, MD • Samantha Sherman, MD • Kevin Y. Pei, MD OVERVIEW CONFERENCE PREP RESOURCES Learning Objectives Anatomic Considerations In penetrating trauma to the neck, cervical blood vessels are the most commonly injured structures. Zones of the neck are: Zone III: angle of mandible to skull base Zone II: cricothyroid to angle of mandible. Penetrating injuries occur most frequently in this zone (47%). Zone I: sternal notch to cricothyroid The vertebral artery is made up of four segments. Injuries to this artery occur in less than 1% of all trauma admissions. V4 (intradural or intracranial): extends from the dura mater to their confluence to form the basilar artery V3 (atlantic; extradural or extraspinal): extends from C2 to the dura mater. It is the most commonly injured segment in basilar skull fracture. V2 (foraminal): extends from the transverse foramen of C6 to the transverse foramen of C2 V1 (preforaminal): extends from vertebral artery origin off the subclavian artery to the transverse foramen of C6 Key anatomic structures of the neck are discussed in more detail in the SCORE module Initial Diagnosis and Management of Neck Trauma. Epidemiology and Etiology The incidence of blunt cerebrovascular injury (BCVI) in trauma patients is 1% to 2%. Motor vehicle crashes are a major cause of BCVIs. Many injuries occur when a blood vessel is stretched over the cervical vertebrae. This results in damage to the tunica intima. Hyperextension and rotation are important mechanisms in BCVI. The incidence of penetrating neck wounds in trauma patients is approximately 10%. In patients presenting with penetrating neck injuries, it is important to determine the mechanism of penetration as this may provide insight into the extent of tissue damage and guide diagnostic and therapeutic options. Vascular injuries are the most common type of cervical injuries and are associated with up to 40% of complications related to penetrating neck injuries, with approximately 10% of patients suffering injuries to the carotid artery. The mortality rate for penetrating neck injuries is estimated to range from 3-6%, with 50% of deaths associated with hemorrhage secondary to vascular injuries. Direct trauma, such as basilar skull fractures or injuries caused by seat belts, may result in cerebrovascular injuries. Initial Screening All patients who present with neurologic deficit or epistaxis from a suspected arterial injury should be screened for BCVI. Cerebral angiography or a CT angiography using a 16-slice CT scanner should be used. The Denver and Memphis criteria are two protocols that are used to identify patients at high risk for BCVI who should undergo further testing. Denver criteria Signs and symptoms Arterial hemorrhage Cervical bruit (in patients < 50 years of age) Expanding cervical hematoma Focal neurologic deficit Neurologic examination incongruous with CT scan findings Stroke on secondary CT scan Risk factors High-energy transfer mechanism with Le Fort fracture type II or III Base of skull fracture involving the carotid canal Diffuse axonal injury with Glasgow Coma Scale score less than 6 Cervical spine fractures that involve C1 to C3 or the transverse foramen Cervical spine subluxation Near-hanging with hypoxic-ischemic brain injury Memphis criteria Base of skull fracture with involvement of carotid canal Base of skull fracture with involvement of petrous temporal bone Cervical spine fracture Neurologic examination findings not explained by neuroimaging Horner syndrome Le Fort II or III fracture pattern Presence of neck soft tissue injury (seat belt sign, hanging, hematoma) Further Diagnostic Testing

file: Management of Vascular Injuries to the Neck.txt
text: Formal angiography is the diagnostic gold standard for vascular injury to the neck, whether blunt or penetrating, although it is rarely needed. The most common method of diagnosis is the multislice CT angiogram, which is the most reliable noninvasive screening modality. The risk of stroke following a formal cerebral angiogram is 1%. Although arterial duplex ultrasound may be used to visualize vascular structures in zone II of the neck, its utility in evaluation of zone I is limited due to the presence of bony structures. The Biffl classification of cerebrovascular injury is a widely accepted grading scheme for BCVI: Grade I: mild initial injury or irregular intima Grade II: dissection with raised intimal flap, intramural hematoma with luminal narrowing greater than 25%, intraluminal thrombosis Grade III: pseudoaneurysm Grade IV: vessel occlusion/thrombosis Grade V: vessel transection with active extravasation Nonoperative Management If there is risk of impending airway obstruction on initial evaluation, such as in the case of an expanding neck hematoma, the airway must be secured. This may involve the use of fiberoptic endotracheal intubation for enhanced visualization of the airway in the setting of external compression resulting from the expanding hematoma. If attempts at endotracheal intubation are unsuccessful, emergency cricothyroidotomy may be warranted. Bedside probing or exploration of open neck wounds, which may disrupt existing clot and result in emboli and/or rebleeding, should be avoided. Patients with Biffl grade I, II, and III cerebrovascular injuries: Antithrombotic therapy (heparin or antiplatelet therapy) should be used for all patients with BCVI, unless contraindicated. Anticoagulation decreases the risk of thromboembolic stroke. Heparin is preferred in the acute setting because of its reversible properties. Current guidelines from the Eastern Association for the Surgery of Trauma recommend against routine use of endovascular stents as an adjunct to antithrombotic therapy in patients with grade II or III BCVIs. CT angiography should be used as a follow-up imaging modality and performed 7 to 10 days after the initial identification of a grade I, II, or III injury to evaluate injury progression or resolution. Operative Treatment Various techniques can be used for repair of carotid artery injuries. The selected technique should take into consideration the extent of the injury, its location, exposure, and the presence or likelihood of infection. The artery should be dissected and mobilized to enable a tension-free repair using running permanent monofilament suture with end-to-end anastomosis. Injuries that are more extensive will likely require repair using either patch angioplasty or an interposition graft. If vein grafting is not an option, prosthetic material such as polytetrafluoroethylene (PTFE) should be considered. For dirty wounds, autologous venous grafts, such as a saphenous vein interposition graft, is preferred due to the lower risk of infection compared with prosthetic material. Cephalic vein patch repair is generally avoided because it is relatively weak and may result in “blow out” of the patch. In the case of severe injury to the external carotid artery, surgical ligation may be performed with limited morbidity and should be considered in the setting of hemodynamic instability. However, for patients who are hemodynamically stable, ligation of the internal or common carotid arteries should be avoided because of the high risk of severe neurologic sequelae. However, if imaging reveals evidence of a completed stroke secondary to vascular injury and no back-bleeding is observed on exploration, ligation of the damaged internal carotid artery may mitigate the risk of hemorrhagic conversion. Zone I and Zone III injuries in stable patients are

file: Management of Vascular Injuries to the Neck.txt
text: best treated with endovascular methods. However, such methods are unsuitable for unstable patients. In unstable patients with Zone I injuries, the best exposure is via a median sternotomy with possible extension to the anterior neck. Open exposure of the proximal great vessels: A median sternotomy provides access to the proximal right subclavian, innominate, and proximal left carotid arteries. A left anterolateral thoracotomy provides access to the proximal left subclavian artery. Extension of a median sternotomy incision to the anterior neck can provide additional exposure of the carotid artery. A supraclavicular incision can be used to gain access to the right subclavian artery and the distal left subclavian artery. A “trap door” incision (left anterolateral thoracotomy, partial sternotomy, and left supraclavicular incision) can be used to gain additional access to the left subclavian artery. This approach is generally avoided due to its associated morbidity. It is necessary to expose the carotid artery for a zone II injury. The patient should be supine on the operating table with the head extended and contralateral to the stab wound. An incision is made anterior to the sternocleidomastoid muscle. The platysma muscle is divided, and the sternocleidomastoid muscle is moved laterally. The medial border of the internal jugular vein is identified and dissected from the surrounding tissues. The facial vein is identified, ligated, then transected. The internal jugular vein is moved laterally. It is important to note if there is concomitant injury to this vein. If the injury is small, then primary closure can be considered for the internal jugular vein. If the injury is large and the only source of bleeding, then formal reconstruction can be appropriate. If the injury is large and the carotid injury requires exposure, the best approach is to simply ligate the internal jugular vein. The carotid artery is exposed. The vagus nerve lies posterior, lateral to the carotid artery. The hypoglossal nerve can also be found in the distal portion of the incision. Injury to the vagus nerve can result in hoarseness, loss of cough reflex (the afferent limb of the vagus nerve innervates multiple laryngotracheal and pharyngoesophageal structures), and dysphagia.
